03890nam a22004335i 9780804766821DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047668217 a10.1515/97808047668212doi  a(DE-B1597)581355  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0080002bisacsh1 aWou, Odoric Y. K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMobilizing the Masses :bBuilding Revolution in Henan /cOdoric Y. K. Wou. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (492 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tEarly Mobilization -- t1. Mobilizing the Proletarians: The May 30th Movement -- t2. Mobilizing the Sectarians: The Communists and the Red Spears -- t3. Penetrating Settled Peasant Communities: The Case of Eyuwan -- t4. Peasant Mentality and Ideological Constraints: The Case of Eyuwan -- tWartime Mobilization -- t5. Coalition Politics and Movement Revitalization -- t6. War and Rural Mobilization: The Rivereast Floodplain -- t7. Revolutionary Reconstruction: The Huaibei Lake Area -- t8. Structural Constraints: The Taihang Mountains -- t9. Mobilizing to Take Over the Cities -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA study of the roots of revolution in the Chinese province of Henan, this book describes in detail more than two decades (1925 to 1949) of the efforts of the Communist Party to build mass support for revolution. These were decades of social and political crisis, beginning with the May 30th Movement, exacerbated by the Japanese invasion in 1937, and culminating in the Communist victory of 1949. Looking for historical continuities and changes, the book traces the Communist movement's trajectory from the cities to the countryside and back to the urban centers, in the process testing the major social science paradigms of peasant-based revolution. The author studies the interaction in Henan between the Communist revolutionaries and various groups that constituted the social base of the revolution - workers, religious sectarians, rural elites, student intellectuals, the military, and, above all, the peasantry. He closely studies the behavior of these groups and explains the social and structural forces that facilitated or constrained the Communist movement. He also shows how Communist mobilization tactics changed to accommodate such varied settings as the war zone, the mountains, and the floodplain. The author concludes that the key to the Communists' victory lay in their ability to maneuver their way to political power, their skillful use of nationalist sentiment, and their community and reform programs that ultimately won over the peasant masses. Thus, he sees the Chinese Communist movement as a dual revolutionary process of power politics and social revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- World. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476682140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766821423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766821/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles